paragraphs.title: 0. A few notes
paragraphs.text:
%md ### Experiment Machine Learning with COVID-19 data and the Oracle Autonomous Database Notebooks #### Remember to change the user, password and url of the datafile stored in the object storage bucket in step 1!!!! #### Step 1: Data preparation First we create an external table with the data from the file stored in the object storage bucket
Then we create a table from the esternal table with date column
Finaly we create a table with data for the country data we want to work with. #### Step 2: Plotting deaths We plot deaths so far #### Step 3: Creating the prediction model We have choosed a times series prediction model
First, we create a table for the configuration paremeters of the model
Then we put values to the configuration table. Prediction interval in days and forecast for next 20 days
Finaly, we create the model on the table, target is deaths column and id is the column with date
#### Step 4: Plotting the prediction The model creates a couple of tables in the schema<> By querying the table we can plot the prediction<> ``` select case_id, value, prediction from DM$P0CORONA_ES_TS order by case_id asc ```

msg.data:
Experiment Machine Learning with COVID-19 data and the Oracle Autonomous Database Notebooks

Remember to change the user, password and url of the datafile stored in the object storage bucket in step 1!!!!

Step 1: Data preparation

First we create an external table with the data from the file stored in the object storage bucket

Then we create a table from the esternal table with date column

Finaly we create a table with data for the country data we want to work with.

Step 2: Plotting deaths

We plot deaths so far

Step 3: Creating the prediction model

We have choosed a times series prediction model

First, we create a table for the configuration paremeters of the model

Then we put values to the configuration table. Prediction interval in days and forecast for next 20 days

Finaly, we create the model on the table, target is deaths column and id is the column with date

Step 4: Plotting the prediction

The model creates a couple of tables in the schema<>
By querying the table we can plot the prediction<>

select case_id, value, prediction from DM$P0CORONA_ES_TS order by case_id asc

paragraphs.title: 1. Data preparation
paragraphs.text:
%script
BEGIN execute immediate 'drop table CORONAEXT PURGE';EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN NULL; END;
/
BEGIN execute immediate 'drop table CORONA PURGE';EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN NULL; END;
/
BEGIN execute immediate 'drop table CORONA_ES PURGE';EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN NULL; END;
/
BEGIN DBMS_CLOUD.drop_CREDENTIAL(credential_name => 'CORONACRED');EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN NULL; END;
/
--
-- Rembember to put your own user, password and url!!!!!!!
-- 19/06/2020 header field names have changed, and other stuff bullshit, fixing...
begin
    DBMS_CLOUD.CREATE_CREDENTIAL( credential_name => 'CORONACRED', username => 'alextorrijoserrano@gmail.com', password => 'm9G>(_vpWk4.c0Py}g}B');
    DBMS_CLOUD.CREATE_EXTERNAL_TABLE(   
      table_name =>'CORONAEXT',   
      credential_name =>'CORONACRED',   
      file_uri_list => 'https://objectstorage.eu-frankfurt-1.oraclecloud.com/n/freztbacphvb/b/corona/o/coronadata.txt',
      format => json_object('delimiter' value ',', 'recorddelimiter' value 'newline', 'skipheaders' value '1', 'rejectlimit' value '0'),
      column_list => 
            'dateRep varchar2(10), 
            day number,
            month number,
            year number,
            cases number,
            deaths number,
            countriesAndTerritories varchar2(64),
            geoId varchar2(2),
            countryterritoryCode varchar2(8),
            popData2019 number,
            continentExp varchar2(32)'
            );
    --
    DBMS_CLOUD.VALIDATE_EXTERNAL_TABLE ('CORONAEXT');
end;
/
select * from coronaext where rownum<3;
/
create table corona as select  to_date(dateRep,'dd/mm/yyyy') as fecha, deaths, cases, countryterritoryCode from coronaext;
/
create table corona_es as select fecha, deaths, cases, countryterritoryCode from corona--- where  countryterritoryCode in ('ESP');
/
